To determine which fields or columns can be filtered in a specific index in OpenSearch, you can use the `GET mapping` request to retrieve the mapping or schema of the index. The mapping will provide information about the available fields, their data types, and other characteristics.

Here's an example of how to retrieve the mapping for an index:

```json
GET /your-index-name/_mapping
```

Replace `'your-index-name'` with the actual name of your index. 

When you execute this request, OpenSearch will return the mapping for the specified index, which may look like the following example:

```json
{
  "your-index-name" : {
    "mappings" : {
      "properties" : {
        "field1" : {
          "type" : "text"
        },
        "field2" : {
          "type" : "keyword"
        },
        ...
      }
    }
  }
}
```

In the response, you will see a list of properties that represent the fields present in the index. Each field will have a type specified (e.g., `text`, `keyword`, `date`, etc.), indicating the data type of the field. 

Fields of type `text`, `keyword`, or `date` can typically be filtered on. Fields that are of type `text` or `keyword` support term-based filters like `term`, `terms`, and more. Fields of type `date` support range-based filters like `range`.

By examining the mapping, you can identify the fields that you can use for filtering in your queries.

If you are using the OpenSearch Dashboard, you can also explore the index schema under "Index Management" -> "Index Templates" -> (select your index template) -> "Mappings".

